docs.abstract: Most of the bad news about the economy is just noise.
docs.snippet: Most of the bad news about the economy is just noise.
docs.lead_paragraph: The economic news continues to be pretty good, especially compared with the dire forecasts many were making in late 2022. But you might not have gotten that message if you watch financial TV: It’s hard to spend 24/7 talking about the economy while saying “not much happened this week.” So commentators — and partisan media — seize on every hint of bad news.

headline.main: Still No Stag and Not Much Flation

docs.abstract: The American economy has long been a safe haven, but it might not be forever.
docs.snippet: The American economy has long been a safe haven, but it might not be forever.
docs.lead_paragraph: Financially speaking, the United States has been a Teflon nation. Bad things happen — near defaults, giant budget deficits, a Capitol invasion — but nothing sticks for long. The world’s investors keep pumping money into the country, which keeps interest rates low and stock prices high.

headline.main: What Would Happen if the U.S. Suddenly Seemed Like a Risky Investment?

docs.abstract: Wage growth and hiring slowed in April, prodding investors to slightly increase their bets on rate cuts this year.
docs.snippet: Wage growth and hiring slowed in April, prodding investors to slightly increase their bets on rate cuts this year.
docs.lead_paragraph: Federal Reserve officials are keeping a close eye on the job market as they contemplate when and whether they can cut interest rates this year. Friday's jobs report offered early evidence of the type of moderation that they have been hoping to see.

headline.main: The Fed Just Got the Job Market Cooling It Has Been Waiting For

docs.abstract: The Federal Reserve is shedding assets at a glacial pace, exposing the financial system to continuing risks, our columnist says.
docs.snippet: The Federal Reserve is shedding assets at a glacial pace, exposing the financial system to continuing risks, our columnist says.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Federal Reserve is engaged in a colossal transformation of the financial economy. Yet scarcely anyone is noticing.

headline.main: The Perils of the Fed’s Vast Bond Holdings

docs.abstract: Are you better off than you were four years ago? Yes.

docs.lead_paragraph: “Are you better off than you were four years ago?” Lately, I’ve been seeing people repeat Ronald Reagan’s famous question, many of them apparently believing that they’re making a slam-dunk case for returning Donald Trump to power.

docs.abstract: The global economy has proved resilient and inflation has declined, but any widening of the conflict in the Middle East could increase price pressures and dampen growth.

docs.lead_paragraph: Global inflation is starting to cool after aggressive campaigns by central banks to bring high prices under control, and the economic outlook is brightening after a turbulent period, but clouds loom over the recovery, according to a forecast released on Thursday.

docs.abstract: More than a decade after painful austerity, Greece, Portugal and Spain have been growing faster than traditional powerhouses like Germany.
docs.snippet: More than a decade after painful austerity, Greece, Portugal and Spain have been growing faster than traditional powerhouses like Germany.
docs.lead_paragraph: Something extraordinary is happening to the European economy: Southern nations that nearly broke up the euro currency bloc during the financial crisis in 2012 are growing faster than Germany and other big countries that have long served as the region’s growth engines.

headline.main: Europe’s Economic Laggards Have Become Its Leaders
